2x.title: Real-world agents should be omni-safe
2x.text:
Omni-safety is the desideratum of an agent remaining value-aligned or failing safely, even if it suddenly becomes omniscient or omnipotent.  The policy proposal is that, among agents meant to act in the rich real world, any predicted behavior where the agent might act destructively if given unlimited power (rather than e.g. pausing or otherwise failing safely) should be treated as a bug.

(This is a policy proposal, and is currently represented using a probability bar because the system doesn't yet have approval bars.)

# Definition.

The Omni Test is an extreme version of [advanced safety](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/edit/8822079447547381518) where we ask, via thought experiment, what an agent would do if it suddenly gained perfect knowledge of [ physical facts], or unlimited power over the physical universe.  An omni-safe agent reliably uses this knowledge and power in a way that remains value-aligned, or *doesn't* use it while remaining [corrigible], or *fails safely* e.g. by pausing and consulting a programmer.

# Arguments.

Thinking about the Omni Test is meant to highlight any step on which we've presumed, in a non-failsafe way, that the agent must not obtain definite knowledge of some fact or that it must not have access to some strategic option.

An obvious reason to think about the Omni Test is that there may be [epistemic obstacles](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/StronglyUncontainable-1) to our becoming extremely confident of our ability to lower-bound the speed or upper-bound the power of an advanced agent.

The deeper idea behind the Omni Test is that any predictable failure in an Omni scenario, or lack of assured reliability, exposes some more general flaw.  Suppose NASA found that an alignment of four planets would cause their code to crash and a rocket's engines to explode.  They wouldn't say, "Oh, we're not expecting any alignment like that for the next hundred years, so we're still safe."  They'd say, "Wow, that sure was a major bug in the program."  Correctly designed programs just shouldn't explode the rocket, period.  If any specific scenario exposes a behavior like that, it shows that some general case is not being handled correctly.

Similarly, rather than design an AI that is meant to be monitored for unexpected power gains by programmers who may then press a pause button - which implicitly assume that no such capability gain can happen in a short-enough timespan that a programmer wouldn't have time to react - an omni-safe proposal would design the AI to detect the new capability and pause until programmer-verified.

Even if it seemed highly improbable that some amount of cognitive power could be gained faster than the programmers could react, especially when no such previous sharp power gain had occurred even in the course of a day, etcetera, the omni-safe way of thinking would say to just not build an agent that is unsafe if these kinds of background variables have 'unreasonable' settings.  The correct general behavior is to, e.g., always pause when new capability has been acquired and a programmer has not yet indicated approval of its use.

Similarly, part of the omni-safe philosophy is that, rather than trying to guess what facts an advanced agent can't figure out or what strategic options it can't have, we just shouldn't make these guesses of ours *load-bearing* premises of an agent's safety.  Why design an agent that we expect will hurt us if it knows too much or can do too much?

Trying to guess its actual capabilities is a reasonable project, especially if there are fallback precautions that revolve around our actual estimates of the agent's capability - but we should always be able to say that if all fallback precautions fail, the agent is meant by design to pass an Omni Test - remain nonharmful or fail safely no matter what new capability or knowledge is gained.

An example of a very broad informal proposal for a research avenue along these lines might be to have some fully general way of identifying 'novel' capabilities with some definition of 'novel' (that is knowably robust to the UnblockedNeighbor problem on 'novelty', maybe directly taking into account exceptionally high expected utility, or pausing upon the mere detection of a 'novel' avenue), and some form of programmer approval that is required before allowing the 'novel' approach (that does not create a ProgrammerMaximization incentive due to some Corrigibility solution).

# Caveats.

There may be a KnownAlgorithmNonrecursiveAgent scenario, or some other solution to the open problem of [relevant limited AI](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/RelevantLimited-1), where some straightforward form of cognitive power is being applied in a way that extricates us from the ValueAchievementDilemma that is known to be limited and safe, while making it somehow unduly hard to put in safeguards that would also make the AI pass the Omni Test.

Oracles that solve problems in post-facto verifiable ways while having very restricted solution spaces are one possible candidate for [relevant limited AI](http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/RelevantLimited-1).  This is the reason for specifying that 'real-world agents', i.e., those that act in the real world, are to be omni-safe.  The real world is a rich domain and probably not [ cognitively containable] in most cases.

7fx.title: Directing, vs. limiting, vs. opposing
7fx.clickbait: Getting the AI to compute the right action in a domain; versus getting the AI to not compute at all in an unsafe domain; versus trying to prevent the AI from acting successfully.  (Prefer 1 & 2.)

7g0.title: Non-adversarial principle
7g0.clickbait: At no point in constructing an Artificial General Intelligence should we construct a computation that tries to hurt us, and then try to stop it from hurting us.
